This composition is a nod to the theatre and vaudeville traditions, which trick films drew inspiration from, particularly magic acts. The use of a stage as a setting inevitably restricts character movement to side-to-side, rather than forward or backward, as seen in the film Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel (1900). The actors enter from the right and move along the horizontal axis, with the camera remaining steadfast, even as they exit the frame.

The frontal proscenium style also dictates that shots tend to be long and, occasionally, medium shots. Close-ups are a rarity in these early trick films, as they borrowed from the theatre and vaudeville tradition, where the audience would witness the entire performance, framed by the borders of the stage. The actors generally remain grounded, never venturing towards the camera, thus rendering close-ups impossible.

Most trick films adhere to the principle that one conceptual shot equals a film, limiting their length to about a minute or less, depending on the frames per second used. This constraint restricts the narrative or dramatic scope of the trick films, which often focus on short, vaudeville-style tricks, such as magic, disappearance, and switching acts, with minimal storytelling. However, as revealed in a closer examination of The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots (1895), a single conceptual shot can be composed of multiple physical shots, expertly joined to create the illusion of apparition or disappearance.

I've always been intrigued by John Taylor of Caroline, a true champion of Republicanism in the early days. As an agriculturalist and politician, he was known for his unwavering dedication to the cause of personal freedom and limited government. His passion for the agrarian way of life was at the heart of his views on governance, shaping his opinions on sovereignty, Constitutionality, and the judicial system.

Taylor believed that the United States had a unique opportunity to create a utopian system of government, untainted by traditional influences. This allowed him to envision a self-governing society where the natural rights of individuals were protected and respected. He firmly believed that these rights were interconnected and that denying one would undermine the value of all. These rights should, in his opinion, be beyond the reach of the government.

Taylor argued that the concept of the "state of nature" suggested that those with physical strength and malicious intentions were often the ones who profited, but he believed this shouldn't be the case in a civilized society. To create an ideal society, he advocated for a government that acknowledged both the good and evil inherent in humanity. Taylor was unyielding in his conviction that a dualistic morality was essential, stating that governments, as they are shaped by human nature, would inevitably reflect both virtues and vices.

According to Taylor, good principles were those that safeguarded private property, promoted agriculture, and discouraged capitalism. He believed a government founded on these principles would function fairly, regardless of its administration, which would inevitably be driven by self-interest. While self-interest was a fundamental human motivation, Taylor saw it as a problem only when it led to the creation of sub-societies that exploited others.

A good government, in Taylor's view, was necessary to contain humanity's natural evil, and it must be closely monitored to prevent the introduction of corrupt principles. Like many fellow Republicans of his time, Taylor advocated for a strict construction of the Constitution, with a limited Federal government that only possessed the powers explicitly outlined in the document. He recognized that an expansive government would be costly and potentially tyrannical, but he also believed that a literal interpretation without consideration of the writers' intent could lead to corruption. Furthermore, Taylor considered the Declaration of Independence the true charter of the United States, as it more explicitly described the country as a collection of sovereign states rather than a single nation.

Going back to the data in Figure 17, we noticed a drastic decline in commuter log submissions during the third month of our project. It was a bit disheartening, and we couldn't quite put our finger on why this was happening. One factor that might have contributed to the decrease was the onset of winter at our New England campus, which tends to decrease the number of people commuting by bike or on foot. Additionally, December is a hectic time for students, with finals and grades to finish, making it easy for the commuter log to fall by the wayside. To make matters worse, December marks the start of the holiday season and a month-long break for students and faculty, leaving many without a reason to come to campus. Classes resumed in late January, but this didn't seem to translate into a significant increase in log submissions. We couldn't help but wonder if our project's initial excitement and momentum had naturally waned, much like a burst of energy that eventually fizzles out. To combat this trend, we launched the Carpool Challenge Week in March, a high-energy campaign that actually led to a spike in log submissions that month. However, we still struggled with maintaining project momentum in the face of the inevitable dip in engagement caused by semester breaks and holidays.

One of the biggest challenges we faced was the fact that people in our culture tend to love the independence and freedom that comes with driving their cars. To incentivize alternative modes of commuting, we offered a range of prizes, including gift certificates to local restaurants, coffee shops, massage therapists, and bookstores. It would have been interesting to see how bigger prizes might have affected participation – perhaps a shiny new bike, a hybrid car, or an electric vehicle would have really gotten people excited and engaged. We stuck with the same prizes throughout the project, but if we had introduced more substantial rewards over time, we might have seen a different outcome. For instance, if we had announced a bicycle giveaway in December and a hybrid car in January, we could have potentially turned the trend around and seen an increase in participation instead of a decline.

Imagine being able to invest in a security that combines the benefits of an index fund with the flexibility of a single stock, without the hefty price tag.  Enter the ETF, or exchange traded fund, a financial instrument designed to track a specific index, commodity, or basket of assets.  While it's true that ETFs offer diversification and the freedom to short sell, buy on margin, and even purchase a single share at a time - much like a traditional stock - they also come with a significantly lower expense ratio compared to the average mutual fund.  However, there are some trade-offs, such as the commission fees associated with buying and selling ETFs, just like stocks.

On the plus side, ETFs offer a dizzying array of investment options, giving investors a wide range to choose from.  But savvy investors know that it's essential to critically evaluate the benefits of any investment, including diversification, to ensure they truly deliver as promised.  In this analysis, we'll take a closer look at the ETF IHF and its top 10 holdings, which account for a staggering 63.58% of its total assets.  We'll examine whether investing in these top holdings can provide the same benefits as owning a diversified portfolio of the same stocks, and whether there are alternative configurations that could offer an even better return on investment.

To keep things manageable, we'll focus on the top 10 holdings, leaving out the smaller fish in the pond.  To get a better sense of how these stocks represent the ETF as a whole, we can use their current asset allocation to calculate their individual contributions to a portfolio's Beta and Return, assuming a portfolio comprised solely of these 10 stocks in the same proportions as the ETF.  The results are enlightening, showing that a portfolio of just the top 10 holdings could deliver a whopping 16% higher return than the ETF, with a Beta that's a full 0.12 lower.

But can we be confident in these results?  To find out, we'll dive deeper by calculating the standard deviation of each top 10 stock and comparing it to the ETF's overall standard deviation.  Will our findings be statistically significant, or are they just a fluke?  Stay tuned to find out.

I've often found myself pondering the literary works of Edgar Allan Poe, and 'Dream-Land' stands out as one of his notable poems. Poe himself considered it a personal standout. As I delved into the poem, I came across the term 'Thulé', which is repeated in lines 6 and 56. According to Thomas O. Mabbott, Poe drew inspiration from Virgil's use of the term to describe an island north of Britain, which the ancient Greeks believed marked the edge of the known world. However, there's another, more contemporary source that should be acknowledged - Poe's fascination with German authors.

This connection is significant because it highlights Poe's familiarity with Goethe's writing. In his book 'Poe's Politian and Goethe's Mignon', Karl J. Arndt points out the striking similarities between their poems, leading him to conclude that Poe was, in fact, drawing inspiration from Goethe. Interestingly, The Oxford Companion to English Literature notes that Goethe was a celebrated poet and playwright, best known for his masterpiece 'Faust', which was published in two parts - the first in 1808 and the second in 1832, the year of Goethe's passing.

Within the second part of 'Faust' lies a haunting poem, 'The King of Thulé', which tells the tale of a king whose wife passes away after gifting him a goblet. Consumed by grief, the king becomes a heavy drinker and eventually decides to join his beloved queen in death. He leaves his possessions to his children, keeps the goblet as a reminder of his loss, and then takes his own life. The parallels between the King of Thulé and the protagonist of 'Dream-Land' are striking, almost as if Poe was drawing inspiration from Goethe's poem as a way to cope with his own loss and reliance on drink.

It's worth noting that Goethe's 'Faust' was adapted into a romantic drama by H.P. Grattan in 1842, just a year before Poe used the term 'Thule' in 'The Pit and the Pendulum'. Poe referenced Thule twice in his collected works, using 'ultima Thule' in 'The Pit and the Pendulum' and 'Dream-Land' as a repeated refrain. 'The King of Thulé' and 'Dream-Land' can be seen as companion pieces, with Goethe's poem serving as a precursor to Poe's exploration of themes such as loss, loneliness, and a world devoid of color.

Given Poe's admiration for Tennyson, it's likely that he was familiar with Goethe's work, even if only through reproductions of his writings that were widely available after the original publication. As I see it, Goethe's influence on Poe's poetry is undeniable, a testament to the power of literary connections that transcend time and geography.

Under California law, a customer who slipped and fell on a puddle of applesauce in a grocery store could potentially be awarded punitive damages if they could show that the store manager acted with malice by ignoring a spill, even after being informed twice about it, because he was too busy eating dinner. But would a judge summarily dismiss Jennifer Palmer's claim for punitive damages?

Unlikely. To win a punitive damage claim, Palmer would need to provide evidence that the store manager's actions demonstrated a willful and conscious disregard for the probable harm that would result, as well as a level of despicability. However, Palmer's case might hold up because she could argue that store manager Paul Martin should have known the probable harm of not cleaning the spill, given that multiple customers had slipped in similar incidents in the months leading up to her accident, and yet he still chose to do nothing.

Palmer's argument that Martin's actions were despicable is not a slam dunk, but it's not entirely implausible either, especially considering that six slip-and-fall incidents had occurred at the store in 2009, and Martin still failed to take adequate measures to ensure customer safety. A lower court decision from 1979, Taylor v. Super. Ct. of Los Angeles Co., suggests that conduct can be considered malicious if the defendant was aware of the probable consequences of their actions and willfully chose to ignore them.

Let's look at the facts: on October 13, 2009, at 5 pm, an employee, Rick Wayne, informed Martin about the applesauce spill, but Martin claimed he was on dinner break and couldn't deal with it. An hour later, another employee, Mary J. Haddigan, also notified Martin about the spill, and he responded with the same excuse. It wasn't until 5:30 pm that the plaintiff, Jennifer Palmer, slipped and fell on the spill, sustaining a serious back injury. Before her accident, there had been five similar slip-and-fall incidents at the store that year, and Palmer is now suing D&D for compensatory and punitive damages. We're considering whether to file a motion to dismiss the punitive damage claim, but based on the facts, it's unlikely that a judge would do so without further review.

It's been almost four years since I took a course in Islam at CBC, and the discussions we had in class still linger in my mind. The question of whether Islam is a hostile religion was a recurring theme. I believe this question has become increasingly relevant over the years, particularly in light of the events since 9/11. It's astonishing to see how the media's perception of Islam has shifted from being hostile to extremely tolerant in America. In 2001, it would have been unthinkable for a presidential candidate with a Muslim background, such as Barack Obama, to run for office.

The Biography of the Prophet has left me intrigued, as the account of Muhammad's life contradicts my initial understanding of his character. According to the biography, Muhammad is portrayed as a martyr who was often misunderstood and humble, rather than the conqueror I had previously thought. Instead of forcing conversions, people were drawn to his teachings, one by one. This characterization has led me to question the author's intentions, as it seems they're trying to present Muhammad as a gentle and endearing figure.

I've noticed uncanny similarities between the ministries of Jesus and the 'miracles' attributed to Muhammad. The most striking example is the story of multiplying food for forty men, which is eerily reminiscent of Jesus' own miracles. This style of writing makes me wonder if the authors are downplaying the true miracle and significance of Jesus' life, essentially borrowing from his story to create a more palatable image of Muhammad.

Furthermore, the biography often presents stories that seem designed to showcase 'witnesses' and conversions to Islam, but these accounts are often third-hand, based on hearsay and unverifiable testimonies. This approach diminishes the credibility of the stories and raises suspicions in my mind.

What bothers me most about this work is the attempt to elevate Muhammad to a godly figure, portraying him as humble, wise, and gentle. However, historical records paint a different picture of Muhammad's rise to power, and I can't help but wonder if Muslims today are aware of the true complexities behind his story.

It's striking how quickly the teachings of Jesus were lost in the shuffle as Christianity evolved after his lifetime. Looking back, we can see a clear pattern of Christianity drifting further and further away from its roots. Fast forward to today, and it's clear that there's an increasing awareness and a progressive shift underway. While traditionalists are holding tight to what they've been taught, their numbers might not be enough to sway the masses. In the years to come, Christians will increasingly become aware of the historical context of their faith, and a growing desire to strip away the excesses added to Christianity over time will emerge. It will take time – maybe decades or even centuries – but ultimately, the trend of Christian history will reverse itself. As the clock turns back, people will begin to peel away the layers of doctrine that have accumulated, leaving behind a more authentic representation of the message Jesus brought to humanity on behalf of God. When this shift gains momentum, it will sweep through the United States and Europe, influencing countless people to follow the original teachings of Jesus, unencumbered by centuries of added dogma. The church as an institution will continue to thrive, but its influence will be tempered by a renewed focus on the simplicity and unity of Jesus' message. Instead of the current diversity and fragmentation, we can expect to see more uniformity in Christian thought and practice across different regions, denominations, and divisions. History is full of examples of such reversals – think of how the Roman Empire once persecuted Christians, only to eventually adopt the faith. Similarly, our country has come a long way from slavery to equality. The great reversal that's on the horizon will be a fundamental shift in the Christian faith, one that will take us back to the source and, in the process, simplify and unify the faith. A key factor in this process will be a renewed appreciation for the metaphorical nature of Jesus' words, rather than taking them at face value. So, what happened to the original message of Jesus? By looking back to the early days before Jesus, we find that Judaism was the foundation of the Christian faith. The core components of monotheism, divinely revealed religion, and the authority of Hebrew scripture were already in place by the time the Romans took control of Jerusalem in 63 B.C.E. But within Judaism, there was no single, unified spirit – the community was divided into Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and a broader group of ordinary Jews.

I believe that The Jungle exposes the harsh reality of human nature, revealing our innate tendency towards self-interest and greed. At our core, we're all about looking out for number one and making our lives as comfortable as possible, without much concern for those beneath us. The Jungle masterfully portrays this through various aspects of the story. The factory owners and managers are prime examples of this self-centeredness. Their sole focus is on expanding their businesses and increasing their wealth, no matter the cost. They show little regard for anything that stands in their way or suffers as a result of their actions. Upton Sinclair's vivid descriptions, such as "The line of the buildings stood clear-cut and black against the sky; here and there out of the mass rose the great chimneys, with the river of smoke streaming away to the end of the world," paint a stark picture of the devastating impact of pollution on the environment. Sinclair highlights the owners' disregard for the well-being of people and animals caught in the crossfire of their pursuit of progress.

The owners and managers also demonstrate a callous disregard for their employees, who toil tirelessly to fuel their wealth. They're willing to do whatever it takes to save a buck, as Sinclair so poignantly puts it: "So from the top to bottom the place is simply a seething cauldron of jealousies and hatreds; there is no loyalty or decency anywhere about it, there is no place in it where a man counted for anything against a dollar." They exploit their workers, forcing them to work grueling hours without notice, and then discard them like so much trash when they're no longer needed. In the era depicted in The Jungle, the lack of laws and regulations protecting workers' rights allowed the owners and managers to run amok, forcing their employees to sacrifice their well-being for the sake of progress. The book implies that those who toiled and died in Packingtown were expected to endure the deplorable conditions, both on the job and in their living environments, without any support or recourse. The absence of organizations or agencies to advocate for workers' welfare only exacerbated the situation, leaving them vulnerable to exploitation. Unions, which were supposed to be a beacon of hope, often proved to be a disappointment, preying on the very people they were supposed to protect. The workers were effectively trapped in a system akin to slavery, with immorality and desperation becoming an inevitable consequence, as Sinclair so starkly puts it: "Here is a population, low-class and mostly foreign, hanging always on the verge of starvation and dependent for its opportunities of life upon the whim of men every bit as brutal and unscrupulous as the old-time slave drivers."

When authors attempt to convey their thoughts and opinions to readers, they often resort to a variety of techniques to achieve the desired effect. Some of these methods are more effective than others, and F. Scott Fitzgerald is a master of using them in his writing. In his iconic novel, The Great Gatsby, Fitzgerald employs several of these techniques to shape readers' perceptions of significant themes and characters. One of these techniques is pairing an adjective with a noun in a way that defies convention, evoking a specific atmosphere around a subject. Another approach is assigning meaning to a symbol and then leveraging it to convey a particular emotion or idea. Fitzgerald's use of colors is a prime example of this latter technique, with gold, green, white/gray, and red/pink playing key roles in the novel.

Fitzgerald skillfully builds up meaning for the colors white/gray, which he later uses to evoke a sense of uniformity, class, and age in important scenes. At the beginning of the novel, we see the author consistently using both colors to set the tone. For instance, Daisy and Jordan are frequently described as being "in white," and the list of white-clad characters is extensive - Nick dons "white flannels" at Gatsby's party, Tom sports a "white shirt" when meeting Myrtle, and Catherine is "powdered milky white." Even everyday objects and settings take on a uniform hue, such as the "white chasms of lower New York" Nick navigates on his way to work and the "gray names" on his party guest list. This widespread use of white and gray helps to create a sense of monotony and class distinction.

However, as the novel progresses, Fitzgerald uses these colors to signify the unimportance or uniformity of certain characters and themes. This shift begins with Daisy, who, after a lull in her appearances, is reintroduced as "dressed in white" in a "little white roadster." This portrayal reinforces the notion that Daisy has become a uniform, unremarkable figure in Gatsby's life, rather than a fully fleshed-out character. The use of a "gray haze of Daisy's fur collar" and her subsequent appearances in a "white" dress serve to further underscore this impression, making the reader see her as a mere accessory to Gatsby's desires rather than a fully realized individual.

San Diego County is a gardener's paradise, where the sun shines bright and the harvest is bountiful. The region is home to a wide variety of crops, including the sweet taste of fresh tomatoes, juicy citrus fruits, crisp leafy greens, and an array of squash and broccoli varieties. Herbs, tree fruits, and berries are also in abundance, as well as the golden nectar of honey and the spicy kick of peppers. It's no wonder that the demand for organic community-supported agriculture is high in the area, with many local organizations struggling to keep up with lengthy waiting lists for their fresh produce. Organic eggs and milk are also in high demand, and some farms even offer tours of their operations, allowing visitors to hike, birdwatch, and connect with nature.

The benefits of organic farming are numerous, but it's not without its challenges. Without relying on chemicals, organic farms require more labor and management to keep pests and weeds under control and the soil fertile. This can lead to higher costs and greater losses, especially for small-scale operations that can't match the efficiency of larger conventional farms. However, the payoff is well worth it, as organic farming promotes biodiversity and creates a healthier environment for both plants and wildlife.

For a small landowner in the San Diego area, the goal is to find a balance between profitability and environmental sustainability. A 160-acre parcel of land adjacent to the town of Potrero, in unincorporated San Diego County, California, offers a prime opportunity to do just that. The property features a mix of chaparral, non-native grassland, and oak woodland, and is surrounded by the Cleveland National Forest. The East County Southern Foothills ecoregion is home to over a hundred species of plants and animals, many of which are endangered or declining, including the Stephens' kangaroo rat and the California gnatcatcher.

This land has a rich history, having been inhabited by Native Americans for centuries and later settled by cattle ranchers and cordwood sellers in the late 1800s. As part of an original homestead patent, the land was likely used for grazing and wood production for many years. Today, a small farmer might seek financial assistance and expertise to mitigate costs and preserve the property's wildlife-friendly operations. I chose a model farm in the same area to demonstrate the possibilities.

In any negotiation, culture plays a pivotal role. But what is culture, really? It's not a fixed entity; it's a dynamic, multifaceted thing that reveals itself through what it encompasses, as much as what it excludes. It's far from homogenous or singular; rather, it's a rich tapestry of complexities and nuances. Reducing a culture to simplistic generalizations – "Russians are stubborn" or "the Japanese are accommodating" – is a gross oversimplification. While it's essential to grasp a culture's general essence, it's more productive for a negotiator to delve deeper, understanding how that culture's values and attitudes will shape the negotiation process. When we encounter a foreign culture, we inevitably draw comparisons to our own, and this can lead to misunderstandings.

Delving into a culture involves immersing yourself in its history, its prejudices, and its idiosyncrasies. Rather than judging or trying to change it, a negotiator must accept it for what it is and work within its boundaries, especially when the stakes are high or the bargaining position is weak. When operating in unfamiliar territory, a genuine respect for a culture's traditions and values can be a game-changer, helping to bridge cultural divides and propel the negotiation forward.

It's also essential to recognize that culture isn't solely defined by national or international borders. Corporate culture, for instance, can be a distinct entity within a given nation. A company's emphasis on long work hours or a relaxed schedule, its dress code, communication style, and hiring practices can all reveal its unique culture. Even within the United States, corporate culture can vary significantly from company to company and within regions, highlighting the intricate diversity of thought within a societal culture. What appears uniform or monolithic on the surface can hide a complex web of values and attitudes waiting to be uncovered.

Understanding values is crucial, as they provide the underlying motivations of a culture. If saving face or communal harmony is paramount, a negotiator will think twice before publicly embarrassing their company or superior. Conversely, in cultures where a hard-won bargain is prized, negotiators may resist settling for a compromise. By considering these cultural nuances ahead of time, a negotiator can navigate the negotiation table with greater finesse. However, to truly succeed, it's also essential to develop a personal connection with the opposing party, as this can make the negotiation more effective.

We often hear the saying, 'There is no God,' but it's a notion also echoed by the likes of St. Anselm and Thomas Aquinas, two thinkers who dedicated their work to proving the existence of a higher power. In this comparison, we'll assume both are correct in their belief in the Christian God, and focus on whose argument is more convincing. To ensure a fair comparison, let's start with the understanding that we're discussing their views on the Christian God specifically.

Looking through the lens of their writings, it becomes apparent that neither St. Anselm nor Thomas Aquinas provides a comprehensive basis for faith. To illustrate this point, let's examine their arguments. St. Anselm's argument revolves around the idea that the existence of God is found within our own understanding, a notion he derived from faith. According to him, we can prove God's existence by looking within ourselves, believing that the concept of God is inherently known to be true. This idea is often referred to as faith, which, by definition, doesn't rely on empirical evidence. In essence, Anselm suggests that we don't need to look elsewhere for truth – it's within our own minds.

In stark contrast, Thomas Aquinas presents a more traditional and evidence-based approach. He argues that the existence of God can be proven through reason and empirical evidence alone, eliminating the need for faith. This would make it easier to convert new followers, as his arguments are based on logic rather than unproven assumptions. Aquinas lists five logical arguments in support of God's existence: change, causation, contingency, degrees of excellence, and harmony. His core idea is that the proof of God lies in the inherent logic that dictates the existence of a higher power.

It's a story that spans over 2,500 years, one that begins in the ancient times of the 5th or 6th century BCE. A young prince, destined to be known as Buddha, was born, and his life would take a dramatic turn when he renounced the world to find enlightenment. His teachings would shape the foundation of Buddhism, the most traditional branch of which is Theravada Buddhism. Fast forward to the present, and it's clear that the religion has undergone a significant transformation over the centuries. This transformation is evident in the Theravada nation of Sri Lanka, where the annual water-cutting ceremony is observed, a tradition that has little to do with the teachings of Buddha. The fissures between the original teachings and the modern practices run deep, from the surface-level customs to the core principles of the religion. The Theravada Buddhist community, comprising both monks and lay individuals, has had to adapt its principles over time, influenced by both internal and external forces.

As we delve into the discussion, it's essential to grasp the nuances of the terms that will be used. An internal force refers to a change driven by the Buddhist community itself, whether monks or laypeople. External forces, on the other hand, originate from non-Buddhists. Hostile forces are those that intentionally harm or seek to damage the community, often driven by a negative perception of Buddhism. Benign forces, while not necessarily beneficial, do not aim to harm and might even inadvertently contribute to the community's growth.

To gain a deeper understanding of Theravada Buddhism, let's start with the core principles. Buddhists seek refuge in the triple gem: the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma encompasses the Tripitaka, a collection of three baskets of sacred texts. The Sutta Pitaka contains the Suttas, the Vinaya Pitaka outlines the disciplinary rules, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka explores the metaphysical aspects of Buddhism, including concepts like Anatta (no soul), Dukkha (inherent suffering), and Anicca (impermanence). By grasping these fundamental ideas, one can break free from Sansara, the cycle of death and rebirth, and ultimately overcome lobha (desire), dosa (hatred), and moha (delusion). The Vinaya Pitaka sets forth rules for laypeople, such as the five precepts (do not kill, do not lie, do not steal, do not engage in misconduct, and do not consume intoxicating substances). For monks, there are additional rules to follow. At the heart of Buddhism lies the four noble truths: Dukkha (life is suffering), attachment causes suffering, and suffering can be overcome.

The long-standing feud between the United States and Mexico, a bitter rivalry that spanned 57 years, from 1836 to 1893, is a telling example of two nations that couldn't seem to see eye-to-eye. In fact, things came to a head during the Mexican-American War of 1846-1848, when the United States successfully invaded Mexico, securing Texas and the American Southwest as its new territory (Diehl and Goerts, 2000, p. 145). But this wasn't the only clash between the two nations; there were many more skirmishes and power struggles throughout their history, which finally started to subside just before World War I. 

What set off this rivalry was a clash of fundamental values and interests, particularly when it came to religion, culture, and tradition (Schmitt, 1974, p. 30-31). Sound familiar? It's a pattern that's repeated in many other nations that share a border with their neighbors. Where lines are drawn, interests collide, and rival positions emerge. The US and Mexico are not unique in this regard; David M. Pletcher (1977) notes that only a handful of nations, including Mexico and Cuba, have been able to sustain long-term diplomatic headaches for the United States (p. 41). Geography plays a significant role in these lasting rivalries, and the proximity of these nations to the US is no coincidence. 

One major point of contention between the two nations was their differing views on religion, a source of discord that has plagued many nations throughout history. As Sally Frahm (2001) points out, in the 18th and 19th centuries, Americans were just as opposed to Catholicism and monarchies as they were to fascism and communism in the 20th century (p. 86). The ideological struggles between the US and Mexico were akin to the Cold War's East-West standoff, but with a twist - instead of a battle between politics, it was a clash of faiths. This underlying distrust was inherited from their former colonial rulers, the English and Spanish, making it a major hurdle to establishing a harmonious relationship between the two nations.

Diehl and Goerts (2000) catalogued an astonishing 17 disputes between Mexico and the US during this 57-year period, with the majority of these conflicts centered around territorial issues and border raids from Mexican territory. The violence and lawlessness on both sides of the border were a persistent problem that wasn't fully resolved until both countries exerted military force to maintain order (Schmitt, 1974, p. 97).

It wasn't until Mexico became increasingly dependent on the US that the rivalry began to fade, and by the late 19th century, American ambitions had shifted from territorial expansion to economic intervention in Mexico, effectively ending the bitter rivalry (Schmitt, 1974, p. 109-110).

It's been fifteen long years since I was unexpectedly laid low by a mysterious illness that I never saw coming. At the time, I was a nurse, having chosen that career path because it seemed like a safe and secure way to make a living. I'd often heard the same mantra growing up: "You'll always be able to find work; people will always get sick." While I had bigger dreams - I longed to be a scientist or a journalist - this was the path I took. 

Now, at 46 and single, with no savings to speak of, I've been living on disability benefits for over a decade. I'm still struggling to get by, with every passing day feeling like an exhausting battle for my security, safety, and self-worth. The thought of uncertainty looms over me, yet I'm reminded of a hard-won truth: without the unwavering support of my family and a few kind friends, I wouldn't have made it this far. When disaster strikes, it's easy to feel overwhelmed, and I know I'm not alone in that feeling.

My point is this: no matter how prepared you are, life's emergencies - big and small - are inevitable. There are no guarantees, and some challenges are just too great to face alone.

While I agree that we should be cautious about relying too heavily on the government, I firmly believe that we'd be better off fostering a culture of mutual support and trust. Rather than each of us going it alone, we should be learning to rely on one another and ask for help when we need it.

The conservatives in the US often romanticize the idea of rugged individualism that supposedly built this country, but the truth is that our forebears relied on compassion, mutual respect, and shared resources to get through tough times. Those pioneers who trekked across the Rocky Mountains didn't make it to the coast without the help of their fellow travelers.

So, by all means, be prepared. I've got my disaster kit, first aid supplies, and a stash of emergency supplies. If you have the means, consider growing your own food or investing in a wood stove. But don't forget the most important thing: get to know your neighbors, and be willing to lend a hand (or ask for one) when you need it.

The age-old question remains: why do organisms evolve the way they do? Are there any boundaries or constraints that dictate the direction of evolutionary change? It's a mystery that has puzzled scientists for over a century – even the renowned biologist D'Arcy Thompson noted in 1917 that "even now, the zoologist has scarce begun to dream of defining in mathematical language even the simplest organic forms." Yet, despite the passage of time, we still don't have a clear answer.

Recently, however, scientists have started to use mathematical modeling to better understand the intricate dance of evolutionary change in organisms. One group of researchers, for instance, has applied mathematical modeling to the development of mollusk shells, examining both their growth patterns and evolutionary history (Raup and Stanley, 1981). Our own study is taking a similar approach, combining mathematical modeling with experimental research to uncover the underlying mechanisms that drive evolutionary change in the snail genus Prunum.

We used X-ray images of Prunum species to identify key characteristics that can be used to model hypothetical and actual shell morphologies. These parameters were then fed into the software program CerioShell (Stone, 1995), allowing us to create virtual shell shapes that can be used to explore the boundaries of possible morphological change.

In essence, a shell can be thought of as a spiral tube that grows over time, with each coil or whorl representing a specific point in the organism's life history. The central axis of the shell, known as the columella, runs through its center, and each whorl is separated by a continuous line called a suture. The speed at which these whorls grow can vary, and the largest whorl is typically the last one (the body whorl).

When examining a shell, we can view it from different angles: apical, basal, apertural, and abapertural. The most common orientation is apertural, where the opening of the shell faces the viewer, with the tip of the spire pointing upwards.

To count the whorls, we start by viewing the shell from the apical angle and identifying the first suture. We then draw a line dividing the shell into two parts, and count the whorls from this line, estimating each one to a quarter of a whorl.

A shell can also be seen as a series of openings that move through time and space as the organism builds its shell. By tracking the coordinates of each whorl's aperture, as well as its horizontal and vertical radius, we can create a mathematical representation of the shell's growth trajectory. This allows us to manipulate the parameters of shell development and explore the possibilities of evolutionary change.

We've been staring at some disturbing statistics for a decade, and it's time we take a closer look. Indonesia's neonatal and infant mortality rates have been stuck in a rut for the past ten years, and while the country is inching towards meeting some of the Millennium Development Goals, progress in child and maternal health is woefully off track. The harsh reality is that the country's approach needs a serious overhaul – it's time to shift focus from program-specific fixes to strengthening the health system as a whole. 

Indonesia's made some headway in getting skilled health workers present during births, with 72% of births now meeting this standard. But don't be fooled – this figure includes traditional midwives who can't provide medical interventions when complications arise, leading to a disproportionate number of maternal deaths due to hemorrhage. What's more, the percentage of children under five treated for diarrheal cases has taken a hit, and postnatal care is a dark area where data is scarce, with low rates across the country.

The alarming low rate of cesarean sections, at around 4%, points to a deeper issue. The rate is 7% in urban areas, but a mere 2% in rural regions, highlighting the glaring disparities in healthcare access. It's clear that urban areas are getting the lion's share of healthcare services, leaving rural communities in the dust. The issue of vertical equity further exacerbates the problem, with a staggering 27% gap between the poorest and richest quintiles – the poor are finding it nearly impossible to access healthcare due to out-of-pocket costs.

So, what's next for Indonesia? The most pressing question is how to address the glaring lack of access to healthcare services. Should the country focus on program-specific approaches or take a more holistic approach to strengthening the health system? While targeted, vertically-oriented programs have their appeal, they come with significant drawbacks. For one, investing heavily in one area often means neglecting others, and human resources get sucked into areas with more funding. Furthermore, running multiple parallel programs leads to duplication and disorganization, resulting in a logistical nightmare.

Victorian novels are characterized by an intense focus on the intricacies of the upper class during that era. However, two notable exceptions are Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights.  These novels deviate from the norm by incorporating elements of mystery and the bizarre, which serves to deepen our understanding of the characters' motivations and emotions. This unique approach allows readers to gain a more profound insight into the inner workings of their minds.

As Oliver Twist navigated the treacherous world of Victorian London, his mind became a jumble of confusing and bewildering thoughts. He found himself lost in a haze of hallucinations, reliving fragments of his past and struggling to distinguish reality from fantasy. In one particularly vivid sequence, the sound of gunfire shattered the silence, and Oliver was swept away by an unseen force. His senses were overwhelmed, and he was left reeling from the pain and fear that seemed to have become an integral part of his existence.

This use of dreamlike states in Oliver Twist serves to highlight Oliver's feelings of powerlessness and despair. His inability to control the events that unfolded around him is a refrain that echoes throughout the novel. The shooting itself becomes a symbol of the hopelessness that has consumed Oliver, a reminder that he is a pawn in a much larger game. His lack of agency is further underscored by his inability to react, even when his very life is at stake. It is as if Fagin's influence has worn him down, leaving him a broken and defeated individual.

In Wuthering Heights, the dreamlike sequences take on a different form. The passage describing the long and sleepless night that followed the tumultuous events of the day is a testament to the author's ability to craft a sense of atmosphere and mood. The words "day" and "night" become interchangeable, blurring the lines between reality and fantasy. This sense of disorientation serves to underscore the characters' emotional states, which are as turbulent as the weather that surrounds them.

It's a memory that still sticks out in my mind - working in an after-school program, trying to help elementary-age students with their studies. I did my best to assist them in areas where they needed improvement, but my strengths lay in English and reading. However, one student in particular - a boy named Adrian, whom I believe was in the third or fourth grade at the time - proved to be a puzzle. He was having trouble reading, but what struck me as odd was the way he struggled with certain letters, while others seemed to come easily to him. His fluency in English was impressive, considering I suspected he was of Latino descent. 

As I worked with him, it became increasingly clear that something was amiss. We made little progress until the day his mother walked in, speaking only Spanish. With my limited Spanish skills, we managed to communicate, and I had a revelation: Adrian could read just fine, but he was struggling with the English alphabet. I'm not sure how much this insight helped him in the long run, but I hope he's doing better now.

I share this story to highlight the issue of the language barrier in schools, especially in California. It's not always as straightforward as we might think, even for students who speak perfect English. Reading can be a significant obstacle, and I'm sure everyone agrees that this is a problem. So, what's the solution? For Adrian, it was as simple as extra tutoring in English reading, focusing on the alphabet and pronunciation. However, for students who barely speak English, the answer is much more complex.

There's no one-size-fits-all solution to this problem. The dual language system, mainstream immersion, private tutors, ESL classes - none of these approaches can fix the issue on their own. The key lies in combining them all. 

Firstly, the dual language system is a great concept, not just for children who speak Spanish as their first language, but for all students. Research has shown that children in two-way bilingual education programs outperform their peers academically. Many people fear that these programs are a waste of resources, claiming that the majority of students won't benefit. But that's just not true. If we implemented these programs as the norm, rather than the exception, all students would benefit. So, how do we make this work? Do we require all teachers to be bilingual? No, that's unrealistic. But I do think it's reasonable to have bilingual assistants, tutors, or whatever you want to call them, to support our teachers.

As we grow up, many of us are told that there's something greater than ourselves out there, something beyond our understanding. Some of us attend Sunday school, while others seek answers in temples or within their own minds. Many of us adopt the faith handed down to us by our parents, but others reject it entirely, believing that there's only what we can grasp within our own egocentric world. Our values can shift over time, and we may go on to find new meaning in different spiritual paths. We're on a journey to discover ourselves through our own unique perspectives on the mysteries of existence and to find a guiding light in the darkness.

I still remember a conversation I had with my dad about his favorite type of bird – the cardinal. We sat on our front porch, listening to the rain drumming on the tin roof as we both smoked our cigarettes. The rain poured down from the gutters, drowning the plants on the edge of the porch. My dad gazed out into the rain, his expression a mix of searching and remembering. He'd lost weight and his clothes hung loosely on his frail body. His hair had thinned out, too. I sensed his pain and my own fear as we sat there in silence. I felt a lump in my throat, unable to bring up the topic of how much I'd miss him – talking about it would only make it more real for both of us. I hugged him, moved my chair closer to his, and sat down beside him, both of us lost in the rain's rhythmic beat.

My dad passed away that December, just five days after my 22nd birthday. The chemotherapy and radiation had prolonged his life beyond the doctors' predictions, but it was a hollow extension – what was the value in mere survival when he suffered so much? I remember questioning a God who would allow this. Alone at night, I didn't say any prayers. If God existed, I thought, he'd stopped listening to me a long time ago.

I didn't want to witness my dad's passing, so I didn't. I couldn't watch the man who'd given me life slip away. I chose to remember him by how he lived, not how he died. I knew my dad better than anyone else; I knew he wouldn't have wanted me to be a spectator at his death. For three days, I curled up in bed, waiting for the news. But no one even called me.

I've always thought that the term "Gothic Novel" is a perfect oxymoron - "old" and "new" all wrapped into one. As Ian Watt so aptly puts it in The Rise of the Gothic Novel, this genre is a paradox that has been met with both disdain and adoration. Some have dismissed it as lacking substance, while others have praised it for evoking the 'terrible sublime' (a concept Burke explored). The roots of the Gothic genre date back to Horace Walpole's novel, The Castle of Otranto, which cleverly merged elements from both ancient and modern romances to create something entirely new. By combining the old theatrical flair of medieval gothic theatre with the modern novel's ability to delve into character psychology, Walpole managed to craft a style that would endure for centuries, despite being both obsolete and innovative at the same time.

One of the key elements that defines the Gothic genre is the concept of chivalry. In the medieval era, chivalry represented the epitome of knighthood - bravery, honor, and competence. However, as Walpole and other Gothic writers saw it, this ideal had largely disappeared from modern society. In his novel, The Castle of Otranto, Walpole romanticized the gothic past, using chivalric concepts to critique the present. This was particularly relevant given the tumultuous times in which he wrote - a period marked by political upheaval and unfair accusations. Walpole's character, Frederic, is a prime example of this idealized chivalry. Described as a prince who has suffered greatly, he embodies the traditional chivalric traits - courtesy, gallantry, and a sense of justice. However, his portrayal is also exaggerated, introducing the concept of excess that would become a staple of the Gothic genre.

I still remember the early 80s when the concept of supply chain management burst onto the scene, revolutionizing the way goods moved from raw materials to customer satisfaction. Keith Oliver, a visionary consultant, coined the term in 1982, and it has been a game-changer ever since. He described the intricate process of planning, implementing, and controlling the supply chain to deliver what customers want, quickly and efficiently. The supply chain is a complex web of six interconnected elements: production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information. Savvy business managers master these elements to provide top-notch customer service.

Production is the foundation of the supply chain, where everything begins. It's the when, why, where, and how of production, setting the stage for the entire process. To get it right, managers need to tap into customer demand, and the market is the best barometer for that. By analyzing market trends and customer needs, managers can decide what products to produce, in what quantities, and where to produce them – all while keeping customer satisfaction top of mind. It's a delicate balance, but one that's crucial to success. I should know; I've seen it firsthand in my previous stints at retail heavyweights like Wal-Mart and Target. These companies have meticulous processes in place, from employee uniforms to receiving shipments from trucks. It's a well-oiled machine that hums along smoothly when every detail is planned to perfection.

The supply element is another key cog in the supply chain machine. It's all about making strategic decisions about your core capabilities and outsourcing partnerships. A company might have multiple divisions for a single product, each with its own equipment, workers, and specialties. Managers must choose which division is the best fit for each process, and sometimes, that means outsourcing to other companies. The goal is to create velocity – delivering high-quality products with flexibility and keeping costs low.

There's a jarring message scrawled on a cardboard sign held aloft by Ellen Page, a Juno actress, on a city street corner. The somber words, scribbled with a Sharpie, declare: 'Hitler is alive in Burma'. Burma, or Myanmar, is a Southeast Asian nation plagued by a ruthless military dictatorship that seized power in 1962 through a bloody coup d'état. In 2007, a wave of street protests erupted, the first public demonstrations in over a decade. Led by a large number of Burmese monks, these protests were dubbed 'The Saffron Revolution' after the color of their traditional robes. As the public's interest in the protests grew, the Burmese government initially allowed the monks to gather peacefully, but the situation soon escalated into a brutal conflict between the monks and the military junta, with the military invading and ransacking monasteries across the country. Foreign journalists were rounded up and imprisoned, and a Japanese photojournalist, Kenji Nagai, was tragically killed on September 27, 2007, simply for witnessing a street protest. While the official death toll is reported to be 13, Colonel Hla Win, a former army defector, alleged that many more people were killed, with the bodies numbering in the thousands.

This is nothing new. A government's insatiable desire to suppress dissent and maintain total control over its citizens has been a recurring theme throughout human history. Ancient Roman emperors claimed divine right to absolute power over every aspect of their society. In Japan, emperors are still revered as deities, sent to lead their people to prosperity through innovation and self-discipline. Our current president, George W. Bush, reportedly held regular conference calls with Ted Haggard, a prominent Christian leader, who was once at the helm of Stupid People Worldwide, a fringe organization with ties to the Republican Party.

Some of the most shocking examples of these actions include the 1989 Tiananmen Square protests, where students, intellectuals, and labor activists gathered to challenge the authoritarian rule of the Chinese government. The death toll from that event varies wildly, with official reports ranging from 200-300 to reports from the Chinese Red Cross, which estimated between 2,000-3,000 dead. Another harrowing example is the Rwandan genocide of the 1990s, where Hutu militia groups, backed by the Rwandan government, systematically targeted and killed Tutsis and political moderates, regardless of their ethnic backgrounds. The atrocities committed during Hitler's 'Third Reich' are another extreme example of a government's brutal suppression of dissent and minority groups.

Duke Ellington's timeless contribution to jazz is largely due to his remarkable longevity and, by extension, his boundless creativity in shaping his orchestra. Though his piano presence is understated in many of the compositions featured here, Ellington excelled as a composer by crafting rich, intricate pieces that showcased the distinct talents of his band members. He skillfully created a framework where soloists could improvise freely, while also writing tightly orchestrated sections that highlighted the unique styles of individual musicians. This approach not only allowed him to emphasize the overall tone of the orchestra but also resulted in coherent and original sounds that perfectly suited each piece. Ellington's mastery of the individual players' voices and how they blended together in a growing ensemble enabled him to write some of the most innovative and brilliant pieces in jazz history.

The Grove Music dictionary highlights Ellington's innovative approach to sound and his use of voice as a jazz instrument in his long career, citing Creole Love Call as a prime example. This early piece showcases Ellington's ability to incorporate voice without lyrics, adding texture and depth to the music. The song's twelve-bar blues structure, featuring six distinct choruses, demonstrates Ellington's skill in complementing the style of his soloists. The choruses unfold as follows:

Chorus 1: A call-and-response exchange between voice and reeds, with the voice beginning smooth and melodic before transitioning to a rougher sound towards the end.
Chorus 2: A muted trumpet solo elaborates on the basic melody, emphasizing several extended blue notes.
Chorus 3: A sweeping clarinet solo in a high register, accompanied by a subtle syncopated piano phrase.
Chorus 4: The full band echoes the first chorus, with a call-and-response between the brass and reed sections.
Chorus 5: The climactic chorus, as the reeds initiate the call-and-response in a high register, backed by syncopated stop time from the brass and rhythm sections.
Chorus 6: A return to the structure of the first chorus, with call-and-response between voice and reeds. In this final chorus, the voice takes on the sound of the "growl" technique, soloing as an instrument.

Ellington's use of voice to add a dimension of tone color to his music is a hallmark of his style. In Hot and Bothered, recorded a year later, he combines his skill in tight orchestration with his ear for tone color, creating a rich and complementary sound through a call-and-response phrase between "Bubber" Miley on muted trumpet and Baby Cox's scat singing. It Don't Mean a Thing (If It Ain't Got That Swing) extends these ideas, as Ellington uses Joe "Tricky Sam" Nanton to great effect in introducing the melody on muted trombone.

For as long as she could remember, there was a gnawing sense of discontent within her. This hollowness refused to be filled, lingering since her early teenage years. By the time she was 17, it had become a persistent ache that wouldn't subside. She began to realize that what she craved wasn't a thing, but a connection – a human connection that eluded her. Yet, she found herself unresponsive to the boys who showed interest, leaving her puzzled about what was missing. She often found herself questioning her own desires, searching for answers that seemed to evade her, even as the years went by. Theories emerged, but none provided a satisfactory explanation for this peculiar phenomenon.

Her home life was usually a serene bubble. Her parents were calm and peaceful, rarely arguing with each other. When they did have disagreements, they were usually with her, stemming from their desire to let her spread her wings and be her free-spirited self. They balanced each other out, but she added her own unique energy to the mix – a lively, lovable, and kind-hearted individual who brought warmth to those around her.

However, today was different. As she wandered from room to room, seeking inspiration, the sound of her mother's distressed cry pierced the air from the kitchen. She rushed in, panic setting in as she frantically asked, "Mom, what's wrong?!" Her mother lay on the ground, wincing in pain, repeating "Ow" in short, labored gasps. Her daughter rushed to her side, placing a supporting hand on her mother's shoulder. "Ouch... sweetie, I need you to take me to the hospital," her mother managed to say, her words strained and urgent. The daughter sprang into action, grateful for the strength she'd gained from prior training, as she carefully lifted her mother and helped her to the car.

The hospital's antiseptic scent and eerie atmosphere hung in the air, weighed down by an undercurrent of fear. Yet, her focus remained on her mother's well-being as she quickly guided her into a treatment room and called for medical help. The doctors and nurses rushed in, and soon her mother was being tended to, while she sat anxiously waiting.

It turned out her mother had taken a tumble off a stool while trying to retrieve a vase from the top cabinet.

I've always been fascinated by the profound impact of diet on our well-being, particularly when it comes to the Mediterranean diet, also known as "Med diet." This study aimed to uncover the relationship between adherence to a modified version of the Med diet, dubbed the "alternate Mediterranean (aMed) diet," and the risk of chronic heart disease (CHD) and stroke. The aMed diet is characterized by a higher intake of plant-based foods, monounsaturated fats, and fish, alongside a lower consumption of animal products and saturated fats. Moderate amounts of alcohol are also allowed.

Past studies have demonstrated a clear inverse correlation between adherence to the Med diet and the risk of total and cardiovascular (CVD) mortality. Another study showed that the Med diet outperformed a low-fat diet in promoting weight loss and lowering the ratio of total to high-density lipoprotein cholesterol in obese individuals. However, previous research has focused primarily on mortality and weight loss, leaving the relationship between the Med diet and stroke or stroke mortality largely unexplored.

This study followed a staggering 74,886 women, aged 38 to 63, who were participants in the Nurses' Health Study, a cohort study that observes 121,700 female nurses across 11 US states. Over the course of 20 years, from 1984 to 2004, the researchers computed an aMed diet score six times, using self-reported "food frequency questionnaires" that gauged nutrient intake over the preceding year. An impressive 95% of the nurses remained part of the study throughout this period. The questionnaires were validated through medical and hospital records, autopsy reports, and death certificates. For cases where records were unavailable, "probable" cases were included, accounting for around 17% of all strokes and 24% of nonfatal myocardial infarcts.

To minimize random variation and better capture long-term dietary intake, the researchers calculated cumulative averages of the aMed score from the repeated questionnaires. They also adjusted for potential confounders, such as age, smoking status, body mass index, menopausal status, postmenopausal hormone use, multivitamin intake, alcohol consumption, physical activity, and aspirin use.

Using Cox proportional-hazard modeling, the researchers examined the association between an aMed score and the risk of CHD and stroke, with separate models for fatal and nonfatal CHD and stroke types. The results showed that greater adherence to the Mediterranean diet, as reflected by a higher aMed diet score, was linked to a lower risk of incident CHD and stroke in women. During the 20-year follow-up period, 2391 incident cases of CHD, 1763 incident cases of stroke, and 1077 cardiovascular disease deaths (fatal CHD and strokes combined) were identified. Women in the top aMed quintile were at a lower risk for both CHD and stroke compared to those in the bottom quintile (relative risk [RR], 0.71).

It's hard to believe it's been over a decade since the United States was rocked by a devastating financial crisis. The job market was decimated, the housing market imploded, and some of the country's biggest and most influential corporations were left reeling. As we look back, it's time to ask the tough questions: what led to this disaster, and how can we prevent it from happening again? In a nutshell, the crisis was a direct result of reckless and naive decision-making by politicians who put pressure on banks and financial institutions to issue sub-prime loans into a fragile and underdeveloped financial system. Meanwhile, Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac got caught up in the chaos, forced to buy and repackage these dodgy mortgages into complex financial instruments like CDOs and CDSs. When homebuyers defaulted on these loans, the banks were left with huge losses, which they then passed on to the rest of the economy.

Looking back, the roots of the financial crisis lay in the late 1990s, when President Clinton was looking to secure a second term in office. To boost his popularity, his administration relaxed lending regulations, setting the stage for the sub-prime disaster that would unfold seven years later. Stephen Holmes of the New York Times sounded the alarm in 1999, warning that Fannie Mae was under pressure to expand mortgage lending to low-income borrowers and maintain its profits. He foresaw the consequences of this reckless approach: "But the government-subsidized corporation may run into trouble in an economic downturn, prompting a government rescue similar to that of the savings and loan industry in the 1980s." As we now know, ill-advised lending would ultimately lead to an economic meltdown.

A perfect storm of factors contributed to the economic collapse, including the proliferation of complex mortgage products like adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and collateralized debt obligations (CDOs). These instruments tied more and more sectors of the economy to the housing market, leaving households and financial markets overexposed and vulnerable to even minor changes in the housing market. When the housing bubble burst, the financial institutions that had bought these mortgage-backed securities were left reeling. The five biggest U.S. investment banks reported a staggering $4.1 trillion in mortgage debt in 2007, equivalent to about 30% of the country's GDP. In the end, Bear Stearns and Merrill Lynch were sold at fire-sale prices, Lehman Brothers was dismantled, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley were forced to transform into commercial banks subject to tough regulations. Fannie and Freddie were saddled with $5 trillion in mortgage debt and were taken under government control in September 2008.

The pitfalls of exposition - that great expanse of narrative where the unwary writer's wings can falter, leaving readers yawning and scrambling for the "Back" button.  Dr. Merlin has been known to let out a frustrated cry at her screen when she finds herself bogged down in a sea of unnecessary detail. Exposition can be a necessary evil, but it's not exactly the most exciting part of writing.

Even seasoned authors like Dr. Merlin often struggle with the temptation to dump too much information on their readers, forgetting the cardinal rule: "Show, don't tell."  The goal is to engage, not to lecture or recite a laundry list of facts. Exposition is like that pesky little voice in your head that says, "Let's get this over with, so we can get to the good stuff." But what's the "good stuff" if not a rich tapestry of characters, plot, and emotion?

Take, for instance, a scenario where a writer tells us that a heroine met her beloved at a certain time and place, got married in a grand ceremony, and then had her husband brutally murdered in front of her eyes.  Would it be wise to spend two pages on this sequence, with nary a word of dialogue between the two?  Probably not.  Instead, the author should take the time to flesh out the husband's character - his words, his mannerisms, the way he loves his wife.  We should see the heroine's transformation, her growth, her dependence on him.  By doing so, we become invested in their relationship, their fate, and the heroine's emotional journey.

In short, we crave more than just the bare bones of a storyline: "They met, they married, he died."  We want the meat that makes it real, that makes us care.  So, as writers, let's resist the urge to speed through the exposition and focus on crafting a narrative that truly comes alive.

I caught two newscasts from Columbus, Ohio. The first one was NBC 4, live this morning (August 13, 2011). The lead story was a disturbing one about a man in Ashley, Ohio who'd stabbed his wife. The news team didn't reveal her name, but showed a mugshot of the perpetrator, Shad Hostettler. He looked every bit the part of a malevolent figure. The report was concise, lasting only about two minutes, as the story was still unfolding. I thought they gave it enough airtime.

The next story I saw was about an 18-year-old named Travis Buyers, who'd been shot in the Sharon Woods area. He was critically injured but no arrests had been made. The SWAT Team was on the case. This particular story seemed short-lived, and I suspect it might have been due to the fact that the victim and the neighborhood were from a minority background. I've noticed for years that crimes committed against minorities often get glossed over, while the media goes into frenzy when a white victim is involved.

The news cycle then shifted to a story about a gunshot hole found in a Med-Flight helicopter. They provided details about where the incident likely occurred and revealed that a .22 caliber bullet from a rifle was to blame. Crime-Stoppers was offering a substantial reward for any information leading to the shooter's capture.

Next up was a brief report about the impending rain and thunderstorms forecasted for Saturday afternoon. The temperature was expected to remain steady in the mid to low eighties for the weekend, but they seemed to be teasing the story rather than providing a thorough update.

They also ran with a story about a robbery at a Clime Road UDF in Columbus. The perpetrator was described as a dark-skinned black man wearing a hoodie and standing about six feet tall and weighing 150 pounds. I was struck by how much emphasis was placed on his skin color and the fact that he was dark-skinned. It seemed an unusual amount of time was dedicated to these unnecessary details.

Another story featured Rene Rodriguez, a convicted Texas Drug-Kingpin, who'd been found guilty of conspiring to distribute large quantities of marijuana from Texas to Ohio. I was puzzled by the way his sentence was reported - instead of saying he was sentenced to 25 years in prison, they said "300 months." I'm not sure if they thought this phrasing sounded harsher or if it was just a quirk. They also highlighted his Hispanic heritage, but I'm not convinced it was relevant to the story.

The connection between brothers is a complex and unbreakable one, woven with threads of love, pride, jealousy, and cruelty. It's a bond that transcends words and understanding, one that can only be truly grasped by those who have experienced it firsthand. Brothers have a unique ability to see themselves reflected in one another, a characteristic that becomes starkly apparent in the most trying of times. Whether the emotions that arise from this bond are positive or negative, they come with a steep price. To truly comprehend the intricacies of fraternal love, one must confront the consequences that come with it. Looking into the eyes of a brother is like gazing into a mirror, revealing a person's true nature, beyond the façade that others may see. It's in their actions and the aftermath of those actions that a person's character is truly revealed. 

In James Hurst's poignant tale, "The Scarlet Ibis," this theme is masterfully explored through the complex relationships between two brothers. Against the backdrop of a lush, vividly described landscape, their journey unfolds as a poignant exploration of the messy emotions that accompany brotherhood. Bitter disappointment and intense pride collide in a heart-wrenching climax, resulting in a sobering conclusion that leaves only one brother standing. The narrative weaves together a nuanced portrait of the protagonist and his younger brother, Doodle, whose fragile existence is marked by a weak heart that renders him unsuitable for the physical pursuits that the older brother had envisioned for them. The older brother's desire for a companion to share in his adventures is met with crushing disappointment, leading him to harbor feelings of resentment towards his sibling. His anger is almost palpable, as he recalls contemplating the unthinkable – suffocating Doodle with a pillow. However, a single, radiant smile from his brother is enough to melt his resolve, revealing a glimmer of the love that lies beneath his surface. This tender moment suggests that his capacity for cruelty may not be as strong as he initially thought. Throughout the narrative, the reader is left to ponder the complexities of brotherly love and the far-reaching consequences that it entails.

We've all seen the incredible complexity of the human brain. As technology has advanced, so have the metaphors we use to describe it. From the primitive wax tablet to the modern computer, our understanding of the brain has evolved significantly. However, it's essential to remember that these metaphors have their limitations and can lead to misconceptions.

When sensory information enters our brains, it's like a puzzle, with our sensory organs transforming physical stimuli into electrochemical signals. The brain's algorithms process this information in layers, both from the bottom up and from the top down. For instance, when gazing at a picture of a black box on a white background, the brain's bottom-up processing starts by identifying the colors, orientation, and borders of the object, ultimately concluding that you're looking at a box. Meanwhile, top-down processing uses the decisions made at earlier stages to speed up your recognition, determining whether you're looking at a box or a hole in the background.

Once the brain has processed the information to a certain degree, an attention filter kicks in to determine which signals are most important and which cognitive processes should be engaged. For example, although your brain processes every blade of grass when you look down at your shoes, a healthy attention filter prevents you from noticing them individually. On the other hand, you might pick out your name even in a noisy room.

The brain's processing is a multi-stage process, with results modulated by attention at each stage. For information to be processed, it must first be stored in the brain. There are various types of memory, including sensory, working, and long-term memory. When information is first stored, it's encoded in a specific way, depending on the type of sensory input. For instance, verbal input can be encoded based on its appearance, sound, or meaning.

Once information is stored, it must be maintained. Research suggests that working memory, which stores information for about 20 seconds, relies on an electrical signal looping through a particular series of neurons for a short period. Long-term memory, on the other hand, is thought to be maintained through the structure of certain proteins.

There are numerous models of how knowledge is organized in the brain, ranging from how humans retrieve memories to computer science and neurophysiology. The semantic network model proposes that there are nodes representing concepts, linked based on their relatedness. For example, in this model, "chair" might be linked to "table," which can be linked to "wooden," and so on.

Aldous Huxley paints a chilling picture of a dystopian world in his novel Brave New World, where technology and capitalism are intertwined to create a society where the individual is subjugated to the collective. The people of this world value community above all else, and from a very young age, they're conditioned to prioritize instant gratification. The citizens of this world are mere pawns in a grand game, forced to adhere to a single ideology dictated by the World Controller. Examining Huxley's work through the lens of Marxist theory reveals a deep-seated distrust of the systems he saw emerging around him. Key Marxist concepts like homogeny and reification abound, solidifying the notion that Brave New World is a scathing critique of the economic system of his time.

The capitalist machinery is cleverly satirized by Huxley through the concept of false consciousness. The average citizen is oblivious to the true nature of their economic relationships with other classes, consumed instead by their own self-interest. This is achieved through the ideological control of the proletariat and common laborers, a phenomenon that's starkly evident in the conditioning of the people in Brave New World. The lower classes, categorized as Deltas and Gammas, lack any genuine sense of self-determination; hypnopædia is used to fuel their desire to consume and indulge above all else. This manipulation is orchestrated by the World Controller, demonstrating the grip of hegemony – the idea that dominant social groups control and dominate others.

The lower classes are unwittingly complicit in this system, mindlessly buying into an ideology that sustains it. Meanwhile, the upper classes, like the Alphas and Betas, are cognizant of the manipulation but choose to do nothing, perpetuating the status quo. The interactions between characters in Brave New World are superficial, devoid of genuine relationships and depth. Huxley may be suggesting that the union of technology and capitalism extinguishes humanity's capacity for free will and self-expression. The absence of true love and deep emotions is evident in the shallow conversations between characters, often revolving around physical appearance and surface-level interactions. The complacency of each social class within their designated hierarchy is a telling indicator of the insidious effects of capitalism on the proletariat, as they're led to believe their superiority is tied to their ability to conform and consume.

I've been a student here at University Park for nearly three years now - roughly four and a half semesters. As a student, I'm not alone in my struggles to navigate this sprawling campus. My freshman year, I was stuck in an East Halls dorm room, on the far eastern edge of campus, excluding the stadium and Bryce Jordan Center. Traveling from my home in Stuart Hall to classes in buildings like Willard, which are centrally located, could take up to 25 minutes on foot, especially when the weather turns gloomy, which it often does in State College.  I had a chance conversation with an alum not much older than me, and it turned out that not so long ago, the East Halls dorms were separated from the rest of the campus by massive empty tracts of land. Fast forward to today, and that vacant space has been filled in with sports fields, brand-new buildings, and a series of apartments. As our campus continues to expand, getting from one place to another is becoming increasingly difficult. So, what's the solution to this mobility conundrum? On a college campus, the answer is clear: the humble bicycle. But having a bike is just the starting point. Students need to ride them regularly, and the campus needs to be designed with cyclists in mind.

I recently caught up with a friend who's recently dusted off his bike after a few years away from cycling. He mused to me, "Bikes are great - for a few years it wasn't cool to ride a bike, but it's the only way to get around." Not only is cycling good for your physical health, it's also the most efficient mode of transportation. With a bowl of oatmeal and some physical exertion, you can cover 30 miles or more. As an off-campus resident, just like many of my peers, I've made the smart decision to buy a bike this year. With classes in Thomas building, which is a 25-minute walk from my home, I can significantly cut down that time to just 5 minutes if I pedal hard enough.
